Barack Obama will be the fourth US president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway, to spend 26 hours there and be the fourth US president in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The diploma, medal and check for $1.4 million will be awarded to him, among other things, for his exceptional efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and collaboration between nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and will have a busy schedule.
He will first go to the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the very first time the five members of the Committee who chose him in October from among 172 people and 33 organisations.
The planning of the presidential couple then provides for an interview with the King of Norway Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will culminate in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American president to receive it, but only the third to be awarded the prize in the Committee&#39;s own chambers.
The White House gave advance notice that Obama would speak about the war in Afghanistan during the award presentation.
The president does not want to avoid this subject because he is aware that he is receiving this award by being a president who is fighting a war in two countries at the moment.
He bolstered the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to point out.
During the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 1.1 million Euros).
He intends to donate them to charities, but he has not yet decided which ones.
His busy program will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the King and Queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant at this award at first.
He mentioned for example having the feeling of not fully deserving it.
He also repeated several times that this is not a prize for him alone, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
Upon the announcement, he said it would be a &quot;call to action&quot; for him.
