United States: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It even becomes comical, the assiduous effort with which Barack Obama, president with a reputation for wisdom, reproduces the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan question, which he himself considered quite simple.
When he finally leaked his long-awaited doctrine, it turned out that he had copied it on carbon paper from Bush&#39;s Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not content with using the expression &quot;as in Iraq&quot; several times in the text itself, he did not hesitate, what is more, to use the title of Bush&#39;s January 2007 speech as the title of his own speech: &quot; A new road ahead&quot;
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush&#39;s idea of sending new reinforcements to an Iraq consumed by civil war as &quot;irresponsible and a decision catastrophic in its consequences.&quot;
The following months, however, showed that Bush&#39;s strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed, to such an extent that the newspapers today do not mention Iraq at all.
This did not improve Bush&#39;s reputation, though, objectively speaking, he left his successor with a much more favorable final situation than one could hope for.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again the campaign commanders who asked him for an increase in the military contingent, in particular the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the reluctance of the White House despite habits of subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to be able to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but for lack of a better option, he at least cheated the general out of 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to squeeze out the promise of another 5,000 from Europe, even though he had originally counted on 10,000.
What causes the most problems in Obama&#39;s whole strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete this whole process within three years. All of Obama&#39;s doctrine raises more questions than it answers.
Many doubt that an increase by half will bring the same fruits as the increase in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor agreements.
The Afghan situation is the exact opposite - no one can be trusted and no treaty is honored.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders from day to day according to what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain only window dressing behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
Balancing the interests of various ethnic groups is singularly complex given the lack of clarity on the relationship, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a &quot;ready to act state&quot;, which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama&#39;s strategy is perplexing because of its voluntarism.
In the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and unrealistic heart can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war for their &quot;soon to return home&quot; will bring about a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will consider it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the will of Europeans to take part in military operations in Afghanistan is moving towards the negative.
European politicians neither know nor want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the development of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the reinforced sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves faced with the very difficult question of resolving the problem through the use of military force.
It will have to be answered, for example, at a time when, according to Obama, America will come to a successful withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
Each such solution will, however, lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only patch for Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to work out a new strategy, in case this one turns out to be a complete fiasco. .
