Czech discovery: a substance that works on &quot;enduring&quot; HIV viruses too
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new combinations that can slow down the proliferation of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality, in some cases, takes precedence over the fact that the combination does not act as intensely on common variants of the virus as well as some drugs already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at present.
We can nevertheless radically prolong the life of patients via a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption leads to a series of side effects.
In addition, the repression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what are called resistant viruses on which the drugs no longer have any effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT in Prague and the University of Heidelberg is paving the way for a way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers&#39; work leads them to discover new &quot;improved&quot; substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bonds to the proteins of the virus.
Metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by the atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon and joined by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the splitting of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
If you stop the HIV protease, you will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient&#39;s body, explain the researchers in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In their work published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic link, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker but more reliable.
The effectiveness of this series of substances on HIV proteases has been tested in test tubes as well as on its resistant variants, obtained from patients infected with HIV.
On the common version of the enzyme, the effect of metalocarboranes is not as strong as on clinical drugs, however it does not weaken on resistant versions against which common drugs are often ineffective.
Metalocarboranes, with their unique mechanism of action and other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications are therefore interesting combinations to be further investigated to move towards drug development. effective against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, director of the structural biology laboratory of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
