Vaccination against pneumococci will be free and optional
Vaccination against pneumococci will reverse old habits from January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
Voices are already rising, saying that compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination are coming to a head.
The pharmaceutical institute already defines the maximum prices for vaccines that health insurance will pay.
Specialists also see clearly in the vaccination process.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccines for August children.
Since January, children born last year from August 2 can be vaccinated against pneumococci free of charge.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If you started vaccination last year or earlier, you will have to pay for subsequent vaccinations yourself.
The first dose of vaccine should be administered between the 3rd and 5th month of the child.
Already last year a quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococci.
Yet the parents paid 1600 crowns or more for a dose.
The vaccination of the youngest requires four doses.
Specialists estimate that each year health insurers spend 300 to 450,000 crowns on doses of vaccine.
However, they save on the medical care that unvaccinated children would require.
Until now the state spent about 500,000 crowns a year for all the vaccination of children.
Reimbursed vaccination was introduced with the &quot;Janota package&quot;.
Pneumococci are the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also of serious infections including inflammation of the meninges and blood poisoning.
According to hospital surveys, there are up to 28 deaths of children under the age of 10 caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced reimbursed vaccination.
Will vaccination be compulsory?
There are notices about a possible obligation to vaccinate in the future.
From January, it must be paid by insurance and optional.
For example the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský indicated that compulsory vaccination would be more positive.
His association has long promoted vaccination against pneumococci.
At an international conference in which our association took part, the specialists were not really satisfied with the fact that we have an optional vaccination.
It&#39;s not ideal.
On the other hand, we are happy that we were able to impose at least this.
I think that&#39;s a direction that we have to follow now, said Kalovský.
But the Ministry of Health does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination process.
We are absolutely not considering it at the moment, said its spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Optional vaccination has its downsides, doctors say.
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the Specialized Society of Pediatricians, acknowledges that voluntary vaccination has its shortcomings.
If all the children were vaccinated, we could envisage a drop in vaccination renewals &quot;In the situation where the vaccine costs such a sum, I understand the decision making vaccination optional&quot;, says Cabrnochová, however.
Experts predict that by next year, more than 80 percent of new parents will have their infants vaccinated.
Vaccination against pneumococci also marks a break because it is the first vaccination of children which is financed by insurance and not by the State.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance companies should release funds for prevention, thus saving on possible future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their products themselves
This is, however, linked to the concerns of practicing paediatricians, which relate to the purchase of vaccines.
The original intent was to have the vaccines purchased by insurance, with physicians receiving them in the same way as other state-provided vaccine products.
Some MEPs feared, however, that this would allow insurance companies to &quot;deduct the sums from health insurance&quot;.
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurance to reimburse them.
According to estimates, individual pediatricians will have to invest almost 40,000 crowns per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It will be far from easy, according to Cabrnochová.
