They learned the lesson so well that Shanghai government authorities, alarmed by their city&#39;s low birth rate and aging population, drastically changed direction this summer and began encouraging young couples to have more than one child; their reaction was instantaneous and firm: never.
We have already given all our time and energy to one child.
We don&#39;t have a second left, said Wang, 31, director of human resources and who has an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of China&#39;s one-child policy, creating two generations of notoriously good-cheeked and spoiled only children, dubbed the &quot;little emperors&quot;, a population crisis threatens the country.
According to the UN, the average birth rate fell to 1.8 children per couple from six when the policy was implemented.
The population distribution, while the number of residents aged 60 and over is projected to explode, from 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050. above the global average by about 20 percent.
This imbalance is even worse in wealthy coastal cities with highly educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over made up nearly 22 percent of Shanghai&#39;s registered resident population, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning Commission, said fertile couples should have babies in order &quot;to help reduce the proportion of the aging population and to prevent a shortage of manpower in the future&quot;.
Shanghai is about to become &quot;as old - but not as rich, however - as developed countries such as Japan and Sweden&quot;, she said.
Gradual attenuation
Written into the country&#39;s constitution in 1978, China&#39;s one-child policy is arguably the most controversial obligation introduced by the communist government to date.
Couples who violate this policy risk huge fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and face discrimination in the workplace.
Chinese authorities have assigned the police the duty to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers have exposed abuses in the execution of this policy.
In rural areas, some authorities have forced women pregnant with a second child to have abortions.
In addition, many couples resorted to sex-selective abortions leading to an abnormally high boy-to-girl ratio.
In recent years, population authorities have gradually softened their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which the husband and wife are already only children -- and in 2007, they softened a lot of their harsh slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research, Peking University, said central government authorities have recently been discussing even more sweeping changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, posters urging families to have only one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who has the right to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city government dispatched family planning officials and volunteers to meet with couples at their homes and slip flyers under their doors.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial counseling for those wishing to have more than one child.
According to the head of family planning, the response has been disappointing.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in requests for records from couples wanting a second child after the campaign was launched, the more urban district reported that there is no was no change.
The commune of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, still receives only four to five requests per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to be only around 165,000 -- slightly higher than 2009 but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee in Shanghai&#39;s Caolu township, said financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don&#39;t want to have more children.
They want to provide for their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and are legally allowed to.
But like many Chinese, they only have the minimum health insurance and life insurance provided by the government.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners mistakenly view the one-child policy as a rights issue, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple&#39;s first child.
It&#39;s true, we are being robbed of the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It&#39;s the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, Human Resources Manager, said she only wanted an only child because she was one herself. &quot;We were the center of the family and used to everyone looking after us.&quot;
We&#39;re not used to taking care of anyone else and we really don&#39;t want to take care of other people.&quot;
Chen Zijian, 42 and owner of a translation company puts it more bluntly.
For working-pair, middle-class couples who drive down the birth rate, he says, you have to be selfish to do well.
People in their 20s or 30s grew up watching their parents struggle in the early days of capitalist China and don&#39;t want to have that lifestyle themselves, he says.
Even a single child demands a lot of parents&#39; time, he says.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are space issues -- &quot;You need to modify your apartment&quot; -- and planning -- &quot;When your child is only 9 months old, you need to write their CV to get a place in the best kindergarten.&quot;
Most of his friends are up for this experience once, Chen says, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to enjoy a higher standard of living, he says.
We don&#39;t want to make too many sacrifices.
The United Nations group has draft plans for reducing emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- so far characterized by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- returned to the limelight on Friday, due to the release of a document highlighting cuts greenhouse gas emissions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations shouldering most of the burden, in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, underlined the remaining obstacles, as much as it clarified the path to be taken.
But it was seen as a major step forward in the time-strapped negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Written by a special UN working group, the text does not say how much the rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, in the short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key questions, including how developed economies and new emerging economies might decrease their carbon output and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature increase that those responsible would be ready to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said Sierra Club Washington Representative John Coequyt.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who authored six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiations text to focus on what UN Climate Change Executive Secretary Yvo de Boer described as &quot; the complete picture&quot;.
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, by 25 to 45 percent below 1990 levels, while major developing countries, during the same period, would reduce theirs by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched negotiations on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion a year for the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to cope with floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, Representative of the United States in the climate negotiations rejected any discussion obliging the reduction of greenhouse gases by the industrialized countries, in comparison with the voluntary efforts carried out by the main emerging economies, if these were not funded by developed countries.
This change signals that the Obama administration is getting tougher on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not insist enough on ensuring that the reductions could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei said the US lead negotiator either lacked &quot;common sense&quot; or was &quot;extremely irresponsible&quot; for saying earlier in the week that the United States would not financially help China to fight against global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of major world powers at stake, fault lines have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about rescuing individual economies than rescuing the planet, with China and the United States bickering over their respective obligations as poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential nations ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was no surprise that major powers were fighting over who should bear the costs of greenhouse gas reductions, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold major emitters accountable for their actions.
It&#39;s really a game in which a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of those countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated they will continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say the negotiations will lead to at least a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which brings together 43 members, drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of the European Commission&#39;s climate unit, said action by small island states has &quot;put political pressure on the whole political process&quot;, in part because they are now unified and that they call on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
Debates became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on resolving most outstanding issues before government leaders reached agreement.
High-level officials such as India&#39;s Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China&#39;s Vice Minister descended from their planes and rushed to the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and information conferences, in order to be able to make complaints which will be studied during the following week.
The true picture of the rally -- at which 13,000 people walk in and out of the Palais des Congrès each day -- of guitar-playing activists put on late-night performances mocking countries they say are betraying themselves and proposals are being drafted and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and as late as Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are stepping into the big leagues,” said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
In Britain, the first 225 km / h train will redefine the Monday syndrome
At 5:13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle will pierce the night to signal the departure of a train that will mark a transport revolution in Great Britain.
The country&#39;s first high-speed commuter train will reach 225km/h as it zips from Ashford, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering the 93km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Minister for Transport, will be joined by Dame Kelly Holmes on board the first Javelin commuter train outside London.
He hopes the new service will allow Britain to join an international network of fast and reliable trains and link major conurbations in the Midlands, North and Scotland to London.
Backwaters will become thriving suburban towns, business travel times will be much shorter, and the shift from air and car to train will reduce national carbon emissions while reducing traffic congestion.
In theory, the three main political parties adhere to this project.
But the ten billion pounds needed to build a new rail network, the inevitable planning battle and fears of environmental hazards are likely to hold back Britain&#39;s high-speed lines.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to produce a feasibility report for the government, will deliver its document to Lord Adonis on December 30.
This will allow him to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next stage planned for the high-speed network.
The new line linking London to the West Midlands will be drawn within five meters of the urban area and sites where the impact on the environment may be controversial.
In the countryside, the plan will be drawn up to 25 meters from the final route.
HS2 is also expected to present three options for a larger, northbound high-speed network.
Lord Adonis will respond in the spring.
Preferred options are put forward in a Y-configuration for which a high-speed line will run to the West Midlands.
The line will split into two at or near Birmingham, with one branch running west from the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another running north-east to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line will cross Scotland.
“It looks like it will be the best performance option,” said a rail professional.
When this is complete, travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first branch, which won&#39;t open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to a one-hour journey currently.
The proposals will allow the train to travel at 400km/h, making Britain&#39;s network the fastest in the world.
The initial route is designed to allow trains of 400m in length and capable of transporting 1,100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can operate on a London - Birmingham line.
A terminal capable of handling 20,000 passengers per hour would be required.
Given the space constraints, it is planned that an existing station will be extended to accommodate the high-speed network.
Rail industry experts say only St Pancras International or Euston offer this facility.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks the scheme should go ahead, but longer public consultations and planning procedures mean a final decision will not be made until a general election.
Even if he launches the machine, the network will have to be built part by part.
Trains will initially be forced to run off high-speed lines on existing tracks north of Birmingham, keeping journey times between London and Scotland in excess of three hours.
This solution seems to be the best to ensure a transition from planes to trains, constituting a reference point for the rail revolution.
