Separatist Abkhazia elected its president, Georgia denounces a &quot;farce&quot;
Abkhazia elected its president on Saturday, just over a year after Moscow recognized this pro-Russian separatist region of Georgia, while Tbilisi denounces a &quot;farce&quot;.
Some 131,000 people were called to participate in this first ballot after the Russo-Georgian war of August 2008 for control of South Ossetia, another Georgian secessionist territory recognized by Russia.
Polling stations closed at 5 p.m. GMT.
Turnout was 58% hours before the close, according to officials from the Abkhaz Election Commission.
The first provisional results were to be announced overnight from Saturday to Sunday.
The five candidates in the running, including the outgoing president, Sergei Bagapch, categorically reject the idea of reunification with Georgia, which has condemned the holding of the ballot.
