For his part, the Georgian President, Mikheil Saakashvili, &quot;regrets that Abkhazia has fallen under the total occupation of Russia&quot;, declared his spokesperson, Manana Manjgaladzé.
Besides Russia, only Nicaragua and Venezuela have recognized the independence of this territory of 216,000 inhabitants, while the rest of the world considers it a part of Georgia illegally occupied by Russian troops.
After separating from Georgia during the 1992-1993 conflict, which caused several thousand deaths, Abkhazia is seeking to show through this election that it is ready to join the international community.
This process is a step in our new life, our new era as an independent state, Svetlana Kvartchia, a 54-year-old historian, told AFP, who claimed to have voted for Mr. Bagapch.
She was among voters who went to the polling station at a school in Sukhumi, the capital, in a pretty white building with a few palm trees in front of the entrance.
The question of Russian domination is at the heart of the presidential election in this region with sumptuous landscapes, on the shores of the Black Sea.
Large panels showing Mr. Bagapch alongside Russian President and Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev and Vladimir Putin are installed throughout this small territory of 216,000 inhabitants.
In Gali, in the west of the country, the head of the district, Beslan Archba, gave a warm welcome to Russian officials who had come to monitor the conduct of the ballot.
We, the Abkhaz people, are grateful, he said during a small ceremony, referring to Moscow&#39;s support, in particular the decision to recognize Abkhazia&#39;s independence.
I hope your country will soon be recognized by the United Nations, replied Alexei Ostrovsky, a member of the Russian parliament, raising a glass of vodka.
For its part, the opposition represented in the ballot by former Vice-President Raoul Khadjimba and two businessmen, Zaous Ardzinba and Beslan Boutba, criticizes the agreements concluded with Moscow last year, such as the one ceding to Russia the control over the Abkhaz Railways for 10 years.
The fifth candidate, Vitali Bganba, claims to support neither the current government nor the opposition.
A majority of 50% plus one vote is required to win the election.
If no candidate reaches this threshold, a second round must be organized within two weeks.
