Managerial revolution or end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees has been reminiscent of the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of getting employees to adhere to &quot;values&quot; determined from above, as was the case in the past, of imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies for conquering markets right side up... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from the factors of customer preferences comes back regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the visible part of a much more general phenomenon which affects executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the company&#39;s intellectual functions, in particular R&amp;D and, even more, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI “requires all stakeholders (…) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision”; it requires on the part of the employees a commitment that the recipes of authoritarian management completely thwart.
This is why we are calling for a managerial revolution that would consist of putting employees at the center of the company&#39;s concerns in the same way as the customer.
The very relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I&#39;m afraid not.
- Firstly because I was able to see that, faced with a new situation, any structure finally manages, after many detours, to do as a matter of priority… what it has always done. !
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from the great engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the American &quot;neurosciences&quot; and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by research institutes and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the &quot;levers&quot; (sic) of executive commitment, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr confirms managers in a posture of mechanistic governance , unsuited to today&#39;s world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies supposes adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of achieving part of their dreams, of their ambitions, of their projects.
Currently, only studies resulting from functional motive analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa which allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their &quot;social performance&quot; and put their human resources management back &quot;in place&quot;.
They thus create a fertile ground for the concerted development of a robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo speech: &#39;just war&#39; earns right-wing praise for Obama
