The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party&#39;s assets.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that the deputies would leave Parliament rather than sit as parliamentarians without a label.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the &quot;directives&quot; of the Kurdistan Workers&#39; Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political window of the PKK rebels.
The party, however, assures that it has &quot;no organic links&quot; with the PKK but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The Court&#39;s verdict comes as the government has just reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures strengthening their rights, in an attempt to dry up Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
DTP leaders had claimed that a dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where numerous protests against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
As soon as the announcement of justice, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the premises of the DTP in Diyarbakir, the large city in the south-east populated mainly by Kurds.
The security forces fired tear gas canisters and used water cannons, while demonstrators threw molotov cocktails or stones, with slingshots.
A hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr. Türk said that the decision of Justice would &quot;deepen the despair&quot;.
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurdish, editor&#39;s note) by banning a party, he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of parties.
It doesn&#39;t solve anything, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
