The cradle of the dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped measured about 2 meters long and 1.50 m high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended in claws in sickle and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues report in Thursday&#39;s Science magazine, Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico which was at the time part of the emerged lands of the supercontinent, Pangea and was located towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of early dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the family ties, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations in the company of other paleontologists, on the site of Gohst Ranch in northern New Mexico
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and member of the excavation team says that they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Triassic.
Scientists very quickly realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
Excavations unearthed the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories concerning the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
Scholars named it Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a quite exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, however he specifies that it confirms certain theories concerning the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, which makes it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the saurians were divided into three major evolutionary groups: theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaurus and the velociraptor which appeared later and from which descended the birds, the sauropods, quadrupeds with long necks , and their relatives and ornithischian herbivores, including species such as triceratops and stegosaurus.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is an early theropod.
This species shows an interesting ratio of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues that suggest that the Tawa hallae had small air sacs in its skull bones, just like birds that are the descendants of theropods.
These small pockets of air make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
As the related line of huge sauropods also possessed air sacs and a light frame, it can be assumed that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
Since the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, researchers have concluded that saurians originated there.
Consequently, the three major evolutionary lines divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is to say all the emerged lands which formed the supercontinent Pangea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there were at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are of course some contradictions.
Martin Sander, paleontologist in Bonn says that there is an even older species, the silesaur, which lived in present-day Poland and which belongs to a group related to the dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give an erroneous view because there are in South America a large number of dinosaur fossils that have been preserved while we find practically none on other continents.
On the other hand, how the dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the branch of the reptiles, still remains a mystery today.
During the Triassic period, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as with the ancestors of present-day crocodiles and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread all over the planet, thus favoring the development of many new species, while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
However, such success does not last forever.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction in which the dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles died out.
Or, the dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate the competition in the field.
In any case, such success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favored the development of a group of animals which had also developed during the Triassic and which since that time had vegetated in the shadows: these were the mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are those of professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley in California.
