The S21 project: a brake for Stuttgart
The scale of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be set high enough.
For its supporters, it is nothing less than “the new heart of Europe”.
If we want. S21 is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg into a desperate chaos of construction sites for ten years. .
Stuttgart 21 was born from the spirit of the 80s.
Terminal stations, with tracks terminating in the middle of the city, had the reputation at the time of being the relics of 19th century transport technology which acted as a brake on modern rail traffic because it was necessary to once plenty of time to move locomotives from rear to front.
Arrival, short stop, departure – that&#39;s what you have to do.
This is why the main line stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart too: a train crossing station, which is located approximately halfway on the Main Trans-European Railway between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava, hence the slogan &quot;Heart of Europe&quot;.
The realization of the S21 project will really begin, although the visions of the 80s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners recognized that the cost of burying the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
To tell the truth, the terminal stations no longer pose any real entry and exit problems since there are modern, reversible trains with railcars and a pilot car at both ends.
However, we are now launching the construction of Stuttgart 21 next to the new route of the inter-city line towards Ulm.
Regional and communal policies prevailed.
The railway company is involved because it is the taxpayer who bears the risk of the largest infrastructure project in the Federal Republic and not the public company.
From an urban planning point of view, this project can be justified relatively well.
The result is an urban space which – judging by the computer-generated graphics of the planners – will be very green.
For the rail transport system the S21 is harmful.
The through station and the widening of the section are designed for passenger traffic which was attributed - and this is typical of the 80s - an enormous growth.
At the time there was no competition from cheap flights.
Modern traffic policy should focus first on enhancing freight traffic because rail transport is much more environmentally friendly than trucking on the road.
But the new layout, with its inclinations, is not suitable for freight trains.
The S21, and this is much more serious, indirectly concerns many other railway projects.
For example, six billion euros will be swallowed up in the Swabia project.
This is the official number.
Experts believe that ten to fifteen billion is more realistic.
One thing is certain, in the next decade this money will be lacking for other junction points and bottlenecks in the network.
The list of the Ministry of Transport mentions a total of sixty major projects.
One of the most important is the widening of the section through the Rhine valley by a good 180 kilometres.
Since 1987 this line has been built in slow motion.
It would be really urgent to press here fully on the mushroom.
But the S21 project has the effect of a braking shoe.
The Rhine Valley route is on its way to becoming the bottleneck for international freight traffic, right in the heart of Europe.
