dream worlds
Some awake see images and hear voices that no one else sees or hears.
It is not only in the mentally ill, or under the influence of drugs, that the limits between imagination and reality become confused.
As long as these phenomena occur during sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie in our darkened rooms, we can indulge unhindered in the wildest dreams and fantasies.
However, someone who, awake, experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, quickly has the reputation in our Western world of being crazy or drugged, or at least of being an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in the mentally ill or under the influence of drugs.
It is our imagination that is in question: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, but which sometimes encourages the limits between dream, madness and reality to melt.
A conscious waking state, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, in the best of cases it is called visions, at worst madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect are distinct, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiments of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the dazes of the shamans, the psychoses and the hallucinations are attributable to very different processes. similar.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of neurotransmitter substances in the brain - first and foremost dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and achetylcholine - is disrupted and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts very often occur during schizophrenic psychosis.
The earth&#39;s force of attraction no longer has power over the person.
Since antiquity, philosophers and doctors have always looked into the relationship between madness and dreams.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of daydreaming; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 &quot;a great resemblance between madness and dreams&quot;, for Sigmund Freud the dream was even &quot;a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it &quot;.
We are in autumn 2001 when Henning T is transformed into a character from a comic strip.
His body is two-dimensional with garish colors.
The gravity of the earth no longer has any power over him, he hovers at the level of the ceiling.
He feels a blow.
Behind him grimacing, winged devil creatures with bloody mouths showing their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels pain all over his body.
Thunderous, mean voices howl, coming out of the walls and the radio.
He can no longer bear these voices that insult and humiliate him.
Henning T. rips two cables from his stereo, loops them and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs on a baffle and passes the loop around his neck.
He jumps.
The buckle comes off.
Let this be a lesson to you, shout the voices in a chorus that tears his eardrum apart. &quot;Go to a clinic and get treatment!&quot;
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last one dating back 2 years, the first for almost 20 years.
She was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: schizoaffective, paranoid psychosis, in addition he is manic-depressive, he takes medication for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
During the psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep despair.
Illusions are a cruel reality.
About one percent of the population suffers at least once in their life from schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is the most common illness after depression.
In a crisis of schizophrenia, the persons concerned can no longer distinguish between the inner world and the outer world, they find themselves in a state of hyper excitement, which means that they can suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relational madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voices commanding, commenting or talking.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the conscious is drowned in sensations.
Like dreaming, psychosis opens the floodgates to a flood of ideas and fantasies from the deeper layers of consciousness.
Reality perception in psychosis is subject-centric, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the department of psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital (Allgemeine Psychiatrie im Universitätsklinikum).
The schizophrenic finds himself right in the center of the situation, everything has a meaning centered on him.
At the same time he finds himself in a passive role, he is like in a dream, overcome by events and cannot act on them actively.
This is the reason why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, manipulated.
In general they have no possibility of adjusting reality, illusions are a cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Experiencing a hallucination once in your life.
Unlike dreaming, according to Fuchs, &quot;the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is perceived during psychosis is fundamentally retained&quot;.
Delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, alienation from experience takes place in a real setting.
Why our brains do this kind of antics is still a mystery to researchers.
Exceptional situations can cause anyone to momentarily lose sight of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies of twins have shown that genes aren&#39;t the only determining factors.
The researchers assume that those affected have minimal brain damage.
It is assumed that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But what still remains unexplained is how the anomaly of the neural system occurs and moreover the fact that it does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger for psychosis, if there is a predisposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses because they act on neurotransmitters.
When our brain heats up.
The crazy thing, says psychology professor Erich Kasten from Lübeck, is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others buy very expensive drugs to get rid of them. procure.
The pleasant or unpleasant perception of illusions is often just a matter of perspective.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and illusory image phenomena for ten years: last year he published his results in a book called &quot;The unreal world in our head&quot;.
Hallucinations are part of the typical concomitant phenomena of psychoses but also of an impressive number of many other pathologies.
These include mental disorders such as borderline or depression, but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer&#39;s disease or head trauma.
Surprisingly, even the brains of healthy people are prone to hallucinations under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that normally are inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that process sensory perceptions are overactive or not sufficiently restrained; when our brain heats up but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like brain damage or psychosis.
But also the lack of stimulus, stress, heartache or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, a third of participants admit to having experienced a hallucination at least once in their life.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and she goes to high school.
A completely normal girl, to be honest.
If there weren&#39;t the images and the voices.
During recess, it happens that a young boy, thin, with long brown hair, speaks to him.
When she answers her classmates look at her in astonishment – no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think this shy girl is a whimsical dreamer but Sarah K is not dreaming, she is sure of it.
She is awake, hearing and seeing this boy just as she sees and hears the girl sitting next to her on the bench.
She can even sense his presence momentarily.
It&#39;s a pleasant feeling, she finds this young person sympathetic.
Am I crazy?, she wonders sometimes.
But she knows well that this youth and the other visions are not real and that they will disappear again.
At night the apparitions are generally frightening.
Often the visions are heavy.
When she is in class, sometimes she can&#39;t follow the lesson because the teacher is just introducing a new student in her eyes and ears while he is invisible to others and the teacher is visibly explaining equations on the board.
At night the apparitions are generally frightening.
When, in the darkness of her room, she awaits the sleep that comes too rarely and far too late, she often cannot distinguish whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the images she sees, the grimacing faces or the girl with bloody gashes on her arms and legs lie before her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she cries to these creatures.
She doesn&#39;t talk about it to her parents or her friends, they would think she was crazy.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She graduated last year and she lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago the hallucinations stopped.
Since she came into contact with the psychologist Kasten over the internet, she knows very well that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough stimulation, the likelihood is high that they will have hallucinations after a while.
I guess the brain not being busy enough, makes sure there is animation.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children when she was little and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she had called dad since she was old enough to think was not her real father.
These are the same areas of the brain that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for actual impressions and sounds, so it is very difficult for people like Sarah K to tell the difference between illusion and reality. &quot;Every experience&quot;, according to Kasten &quot;takes place in the brain, reality is formed from there.
Hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real.&quot;
For Kasten, nocturnal dreams are also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those in acute psychoses.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
This is why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a special talent.
There is only one step between the dream and the hallucination.
In our world too centered on consciousness, we unfortunately quickly tend to take imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and head doctor of the clinic for psychiatry and psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious illness, painful but also containing something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a particular form of the modification of waking consciousness by dreaming.
Oneiroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams which are perceived as real by the one who lives them and which he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is in a waking state.
The oneiroid state of consciousness manifests itself during a trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies such as for patients with polyradiculopathy who, fully conscious, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and of the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation which affects his life, by his own imaginary world which is dissociated reality .
It is a state of mental limit between the dream and the hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a world change takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is in fact a matter of an intense form of means and interpretation, in a situation in itself intolerable, a capacity for organization which is given to us, to us men, so as not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book &quot;Change of Heart&quot; as a soul-saving action.
He is 49 years old, when his conscious leaves for a trip of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; meanwhile, his body is doomed to lie still in intensive care.
Claussen dives into a world he created from scratch, visits foreign places, travels through time. He sees himself as an old man bedridden in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages among nobles who manufacture narcotics from blood.
He is kidnapped by a Greek on a motorbike who takes him to his country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the snowfields of the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
He is completely absorbed in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is an entirely different state, he writes, describing what he experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mind travel are crystal clear and very detailed even years later.
We can even say that they are much more distinct and more intensive than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience bursts the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our internal representations of external reality are even in a waking state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten &quot;can cause a distortion of what we call reality.&quot;
An experience that can also be quite rewarding.
