75% of working mothers have had work-related problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study “Fertility and professional career of women in Spain”, carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, carried out on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have seen their professional careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the start of life as a couple and the number of children, whether the woman works or not and the type of job held.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, form a couple earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with a stable job, mainly in the public sector, postpone the entry into life as a couple and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with a permanent job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling into a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. “These data show that women with a stable job needed more time in their lives to obtain it, which led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of job exercised largely influences maternity, but less so the date of the start of living together,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between women&#39;s age at marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the later they marry and have their first child.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group aged between 35 and 49, those with elementary and higher education respectively became mothers for the first time at ages 25.1 and 32.1 on average.
