Emergency brake assist is now mandatory
As happened with ABS anti-lock braking system and as will happen with ESP stability control, emergency brake assist systems will be a mandatory feature on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a waiting period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, even if, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear impacts.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the kick given by the driver.
But the latter does not always maintain the pressure until the end.
According to a study by car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of drivers involved in an accident were unable to apply the brake before the collision, and half of them did not benefit from all his strength.
Up to 1,100 crashes
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, demands the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance that the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of element, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is calculated that one in four claims with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system which, thanks to a radar or a camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although a collision is unavoidable, the device exerts the maximum force on the brakes in order to minimize the damage.
