New tools for car expertise
In these days of bad weather and accidents, auto repair shops are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have suffered an accident are brought to a garage, where an expert must assess the damage suffered and the cost of the repair.
Every claim is different, and calculating the cost of parts and labor time can be a long and complex job.
Calculating by hand the cost of a repair between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including parts and labor can take two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the assistance of the most recent IT tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
It is for this reason that almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
Service providers and solutions for damage assessment and maintenance are dedicated to collecting information provided by manufacturers, then processing it and offering it to their customers as a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the North American group Solera, is the leading company; 80% of estimates are made with its products.
Other companies competing in the area of assessment tools and industry insights are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with data provided by manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, the company in Spain with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is constantly increasing, so that in the last five years, more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the previous fifteen years.
When a new car hits the market, these companies get to work.
This is a very difficult job, because you have to catalog each of the thousand parts of the vehicle and enter its price.
In addition, an &quot;intelligent&quot; graphic image of each model is created on which the different parts of a passenger car can be clicked.
If it&#39;s a high-selling model, the job can be ready in a week if the process moves very quickly.
If it is a low-selling automobile, it may take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of the cars marketed in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, they have information on, for example, Porsches, but not Ferraris or Lamborghinis.
Regarding vehicles in circulation, the figure exceeds 99%.
To carry out the work of documentation and development of databases, Audatex has eight centers spread throughout the world (in Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them specializes in certain brands.
The national headquarters are located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (generally mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million each year to develop these databases.
Each month, 2.5 million records are recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The elaboration of this huge flow of information allows these companies to give it different uses and to offer various products.
The most frequent application concerns repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing breakage parts or for calculating the market or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that provides information on the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer it in our country, but it does in the United States.
Looking at the products offered by Audatex, it is easy to get an idea of the type of support it can provide to professionals in the sector.
This company offers ten different tools, the flagship product being AudaPlus, the standard claims assessment solution for adjusters.
They include cars, motorcycles, light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of parts, it takes into account repair times estimated by the manufacturer or paint schedules.
This tool is purchased according to its use, for each estimate.
The highest cost is 5.75 euros, for customers who use it little, at most ten times a month.
Then, each insurance company, which carries out thousands of appraisals, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the total identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it left the assembly line, only thanks to its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle glasses, and AudaSubastas is a server open to the professional sector on the Internet that allows bidding on vehicles declared as salvage.
Its statistics service is very useful for identifying trends, carrying out geo-demographic analyzes or knowing common problems by brand or model.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a certain brand went to the garage for a breakdown or how many suffered serious claims for a given period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tool.
It markets, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for experts and provides digital images, as well as access to official parts, prices and times from the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa group, founded in 1971, as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of claims, breakdowns or car maintenance.
The GT Assessment Guide is a historical reference product on the market.
The company works with 24,000 users in garages, 3,100 adjusters and 53 insurance companies.
Its business volume has increased at the rate of 20% per year over the past three years, and it made a turnover of 10.8 million euros in 2008.
At the beginning of last year, it began its internationalization process, with the establishment of an office in Paris.
For its part, Audatex was born in Germany in 1966 and established itself in Spain in 1979.
According to company sources, 62% of its turnover is generated in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. It works with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 garages, 3,000 of which are in Spain.
The global turnover of the Solera group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) will amount to 557 million dollars, 3.3% more than in 2008.
In our country, the company will receive 19.1 million euros, which is 7.2% more than last year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was listed on the stock exchange for 1,000 million dollars, today its shares are valued at a total of 2,400 million dollars.
Since 2007, it has been listed on the New York Stock Exchange and is part of the Standard &amp; Poor&#39;s benchmark index.
Internet auctions of wrecked cars
Last October, the Solera group bought Autoonline, an Internet platform for the sale of damaged cars, motorcycles and special vehicles.
The operation involved a cost of 59.5 million euros for 85% of the capital of the company, which could expand next year to the remaining 15%.
The objective of the acquisition was to offer more value-added services to its customers, with the possibility of accessing a huge international market.
This valuation and sales service is intended exclusively for professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, appraisers, rental companies, garages, scrapyards and professional sellers who must be registered before starting to perform operations.
This platform was created in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650,000 operations throughout Europe, including 500,000 in Germany.
Among its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
There are currently more than 1500 sellers and 4000 experts registered on the site.
It manages 3,000 ads per day and in the Spanish market 100 new ads are published every day.
According to Spanish law, a car whose chassis number has been withdrawn can no longer be driven, but on the other hand, certain parts that are not damaged can be used as spare parts.
Classic cars can be re-registered, although they have been withdrawn, after complex procedures.
Garage quote in four steps
With the Auda-Taller tool, the Audatex company guarantees that the user obtains an estimate in just four steps: identify the vehicle, search for the spare part, create an estimate and generate it.
Ease of use is an essential element of these systems, especially to convince older professionals who, to a greater or lesser extent, are reluctant to use new management techniques.
The database includes 1,034 vehicles, including 666 passenger cars, 109 off-road vehicles, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Naturally, to use it, a computer and an Internet connection are required.
Once the model to be repaired has been identified by its chassis number, a real graphic image of the model in question appears, then the necessary part is selected.
The user can include variables such as labor cost, markups or discounts, and then print the quote for delivery to the customer.
AudaTaller is not an estimation tool like AudaPlus, but a catalog of references.
The main difference between these two systems is that the one for garages does not include estimated labor times.
The cost of using this tool for the garage is 350 euros per year, which can be credited.
Currently, the Audatex company is working to make these images three-dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics see very favorably, since it will allow, for example, to select a door and rotate it to see the internal face.
